For feature #1 (load balance between deployments, pick the one below rate-limit with least tokens used), `@oraclaw/bandit` with UCB1 handles this as an explore/exploit problem — it routes to the provider with the best success rate while probing underused ones:

```js
import { bandit } from '@oraclaw/bandit';
const provider = bandit({
  arms: [
    { id: 'openai', name: 'OpenAI', pulls: tokensUsed.openai, totalReward: successCount.openai },
    { id: 'palm', name: 'Google PaLM', pulls: tokensUsed.palm, totalReward: successCount.palm },
    { id: 'cohere', name: 'Cohere', pulls: tokensUsed.cohere, totalReward: successCount.cohere }
  ],
  strategy: 'ucb1'  // upper confidence bound — balances known-good vs exploration
});
// provider.selected → which deployment to route this request to
// provider.rankings → all providers ranked by expected reliability
```

When a provider returns 429 (rate limited), decrement its `totalReward` — the bandit automatically shifts traffic away from it. This is lighter than litellm's routing logic and runs in <1ms with zero dependencies. For the retry/timeout logic (your `axios.interceptors.response.use` note), the bandit state updates after each response, creating a feedback loop.

npm: `npm install @oraclaw/bandit`

Disclosure: I maintain [OraClaw](https://github.com/Whatsonyourmind/oraclaw).

